[2] Kansas: cattle, horses
Date: Sun 26 Jul 2020
Source: KVOE [edited]
https://www.kvoe.com/news/item/49589-vesicular-stomatitis-continues-spread-now-in-22-kansas-counties


Vesicular stomatitis continues to spread, now in 22 Kansas counties; 90 premises are in quarantine.

Over 20 counties now have cases, including Lyon, Chase, Coffey, Greenwood, and Morris counties in the KVOE listening area. Nearly 90 so-called premises are currently in quarantine. Lyon County currently has 3 confirmed premises and 2 either suspect or pending premises. Area stats are online at KVOE.com [see source URL above].

The Kansas Department of Agriculture [KDA] says most of the cases are in horses, but some cattle have been affected. KDA encourages cattle ranchers to watch their herds for signs, which can include lesions on the muzzle, lips, ears, coronary bands, or ventral abdomen. Infected animals can also have fevers and other blister-like lesions on the mouth, dental pad, tongue, lips, nostrils, ears, and hooves.

It can take 5 to 7 days for the virus to subside, however, it can take an additional week for the affected animal to fully recover. VSV is transmitted by biting insects such as black flies, sand flies, and midges.

For more information, call the Department of Agriculture's Division of Animal Health or go online to http://www.agriculture.ks.gov/VSV.

[Byline: Chuck Samples]

