[HealthMap/ProMED map of Arkansas, United States: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7630192,4354
Arkansas county map: https://www.mapsofworld.com/usa/states/arkansas/arkansas-county-map.html

VSV is transmitted by biting insects such as black flies, sand flies, and midges. The use of insect spray approved for your horse or cattle may help.

This disease seems to appear every year or every couple of years. There are 2 strains and USDA and other resources have stopped reporting the strain in each state. It is important to track the strains, as some states may have more than one. There is no vaccine for this disease and while it causes our animals pain and can stop our transport to shows or events, the lesions heal in 2-3 weeks. Vigilance is required to notice when your animal(s) has/have quit eating, as blisters in the mouth can be painful. In most states, this is a reportable disease and should be reported to the state veterinarian's office of the affected state. - Mod.TG]
